Food debt of European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro area countries, the rate of inflation in November was higher than expected - after 2.6% in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are based on only 3 percent, reports Bloomberg.
In contrast to the American, British, and Canadian central bank (ECB), the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the leitency rate. According to its discretion, the reduction in interest rates would favour rising commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment in the creation of an inflation spiral.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two-percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the throttle: one has to "agree" inflation in order to exclude later needs for action.
With 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The increase in inflation in the euro area is responsible for the rise in food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and the course for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in food oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
In 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
Gallup locates government crisis
After long stagnations, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown significantly by the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has had the largest base camp, while the approval for the Socialists according to Gallup has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent.
In the case of party loyal voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition advocates: more than two thirds (71 percent) are opposed to a fifth (20 percent) approval of the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are under the parliamentary heading of entry: they come to two percent in the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low, the general economic mood has worsened further - the proportion of those who consider the country's economic situation to be "pronounced bad" has never been high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it "very bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families again see the change in their financial situation as pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration in the situation; only one-tenth is expected to be better.
A Gallup survey carried out in December revealed that 71% of respondents - a historic high - considered the work of the Prime Minister "very bad than right".
Thirteen percent of respondents generally have great trust or trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while the share of supporters for Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared to 27% distrust of the head of the Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of the political mood is the number of those who believe that one could get in control of dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister even without a change of government.
If, after the unrest last October, 35% were still in favour of the government and the head of government, this proportion is only 20% today, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked for their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would participate "with certainty" and another 20% would give their vote "likely".
For comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the urns "with certainty" and a further 15% would consider their participation "likely". Given these trends, the outcome of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against the study fees, 79% against the practical fee, and 84% against the hospital day money.
Based on the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty" the proportions of opponents of study, practice and hospital fees would even be 81, 84, and 89 percent respectively.
