In many places disinfectants are saved
Today, more than a thousand infections have been registered in hospitals due to improper treatment of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff - all the factors that are not directly attributable to the control of infections, according to the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places, the disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, an MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The bacterium resistant to antibiotics was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was a similar infection here.
The injury of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not yet been performed because of the bacterium that is still in the patient’s body.
Until 10 December this year, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System were reported from hospitals in 1094, according to the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Centre, Karolina Böröcz.
So so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were certainly registered in hospitals, but the dark rate should be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by the MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about one third of the people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as inflammation of the neck, inflammation of almonds, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are too high or used improperly, the well-responsible bacteria produce antibiotics-resistant, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weak, or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older, or low body weight patients, these bacteria can cause serious infections such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the hospital routine.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, ordered Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to Antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the care staff wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are being examined for MRSA, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Samples taken too rarely
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current prevailing conditions and circumstances would be unfavourable to reduce the development or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and old-age homes, the hospitals should examine the delivered patients and immediately isolate MRSA infected persons.
In the Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practised so frequently.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the public health insurance fund for this investigation.
Therefore, most of the cases would not be possible until the patient has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological investigations are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive of hospitals is not always respected.
Among the outpatients, or patients in basic care, microbiological sampling is even more rare, says Karolina Böröcz.
The disinfectant is separated from the disinfectant.
Scientific evidence proves that MRSA is most often transferred by the care staff from one patient to another.
This is why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds close to each other, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
Unfortunately, as Karolina Böröcz further notes, in the financially less well-appointed hospitals, it even occurs that in disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that directly favour the development of infections.
Such infections are found to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Börecz.
Government programme against MRSA
MRSA infections in control cause health insurance enormous costs, so they will fight everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its limitation, was held in the government programme.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals to be one of its priorities.
