Bulgaria, the EU real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe is looking at the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who is still buying the cheapest market in the EU, but which is getting more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently the most sought-after patch for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Among the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea there are Alena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also more and more in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior also attracts investors sooner or later, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, as well as the extremely favourable area of Russians, for example.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offers highest returns.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive European golfing paradises, thus attracting tourists in the summer and winter seasons as well as in the other two seasons.
Therefore, forward-looking investors are already buying in a large style, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who acquire real estate in Bulgaria are also seeking to change their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested people from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers at the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle, buy either revitalized properties by 50-100.000 euros, or run-down houses by 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication opportunities are widely written, but also the proximity to a large city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group constitutes business people who invest with the aim of a medium to long-term increase in value.
However, real estate in the capital is becoming increasingly expensive, due to the growing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the last five years there has been an annual price increase of 21 percent.
The increase in real estate prices far exceeds the rise in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As Minister for the Environment Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries discuss Bali's roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the post-2012 period, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol has expired.
At present, a heated debate is under way between industrialized and developing countries.
The US has already indicated that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue of the conference is whether industrialised countries are prepared to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on the support of developing countries has also been reached.
The adjustment funds under the Kyoto Protocol are to be managed by a 16-member Council, likely at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be read in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6 percent
Minister for the Environment Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by the 1990 values), regardless of whether the "Agreement after 2012" was achieved successfully, or not. The Union would even be willing to work towards a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrialised countries in the world and/or developing countries are also willing to meet their commitments by strength and responsibility.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objectives of States that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 were a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU and its 15 member states had already committed themselves to a minimum of 8%.
The requirement for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will meet, as can be read in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement has to be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly enter into force only after 2012. In this case, the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, whose importance also the IPCC, the International Nobel Peace Commission, has highlighted in its recent report the UN's scientific climate change committee, which has been awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would slow down the emission reduction, and the increase in the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which according to scientists would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army advertising on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: since March 2006, special units stationed in Afghanistan have been charging videos about operations against the Taliban, reports the BBC.
The film with miniature cameras shot on helmets is controlled at Kandahar Air Force Base and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Soldiers of the Air Force have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been considered more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defence headquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population of the real objectives of foreign operations.
This kind of propaganda has been published almost free of charge compared to traditional television advertising, according to the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures adopted by the government in their own way.
American advertising with game
However, the army must also fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully handled, censored shots, also create the net - such as those that show the death of soldiers: the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films talk about the losses at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, numerous videos have already been loaded on the platform from the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, but this "gatung" has only recently been discovered by the British.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, with the free downloadable shooting game "Amerikas Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less life-reliable simulation.
