Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August with the support of the "Moving for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The Institute's "risk warning report" states, among other things: In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provocation of such a dispute, according to the Research Institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma Hungary opposite".
It is thought that this would intensify the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent conflicts.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guards, not least thanks to the enormous attention given by the local and foreign media, "has significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, in particular as regards confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: Since autumn 2006, the reorganisation of radical and extreme right groups in Hungary has been constantly on the rise, so that since summer 2007 several organizations called "national self-defense" have been established.
"These groups are commonplace that they define each other as civil organisation, while openly boasting of preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (terrorism protection, national defence, order prevention), appealing to the impotence of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And further, all of this is done in accordance with the method that seeks to camouflage different political aspirations based on the political and party indifference of the population as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association is therefore not merely to avoid legal obstacles that could arise in the course of registration at court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
As the analysis shows, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-enhancing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, according to some ultranationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries, in the development of the Hungarian Guard, the confirmation of its own anti-Hungary policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region" - it was said.
From the point of view of the Research Institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the whole region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose establishment was announced by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (GNU) in August 2007.
In the background of the birth of the Bulgarian Guards were the Roma mass outcries that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took the incidents on the occasion of the establishment of the National Guard, with the argument that the aim of the organisation of "national protection".
