Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary holidays are precisely regulated by law, so that the practice of redisposing the working days around the holidays has now been established, but the coming year gives us less such days.
In the EU and in America, too, something else is "feiertag".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and working days.
Work-free days are usually church holidays, or are associated with important historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are unemployed days - the latter alone can rest with the New Year's celebrations.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The public holidays are the 15th of March, which commemorates the 1848 Revolution, and the 23rd of October, the anniversary of the 1956 Revolution.
On August 20th, the founding of the state, celebrated on May 1st, on November 1st and 2nd, we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "workday shift" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be completed, the Minister of Labour has been laid down in a separate regulation for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, to public employees and public officials.
Only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on holidays, are excluded.
Today, the working order is only a little confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24th, life in this country will remain formal, since most of the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve will take a time off, or the holiday that has been set aside for it.
Next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week, or to the end of the week, so that there will be less redeployment during the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "put on the head" around the day of work so that people can stay at home for four days.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day so that Friday, May 2 can be a rest day.
The second redisposition is related to the holiday on October 23rd: On Saturday, October 18th, one will have to finish Friday, October 24th.
However, the end of the year will remain in the sign of the holidays, after everything will lie and stand from December 24th, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
