Data from a European spaceship on a orbit show that the planet is more like an averted twin of the earth than was previously known.
Venus is the nearest planetary neighbor of the Earth.
The two worlds have about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but the Venus of the Sun is a little closer.
Billions of years ago, scientists believe that the Venus conditions that would have been very similar to those on earth could have been inhabitable today.
But because of the unblemished carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by sun exposure and a slower rotational pace, Venus took a completely different developmental course.
Today the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express space probe, which has examined the plants for a year, provide a sobering view of how the Earth could develop in the face of the catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the head of Venus Express Mission, said: "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that of the Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar."
"Our new data enable us to construct a scenario in which Venus started billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with an inhabitable environment."
