After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxen of 1968, internal research in the Moderna Museet in Stockholm is now a sobering result: The six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has made the Moderna Museet 1995 as a gift, are copies - and probably most of the more than a hundred Brillo boxes of the "Type Stockholm", which are in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is nested, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard carton of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his works in the Moderna Museet 1968 - with Warhol's consent - presented hundreds of broillo boxes from cardboard: these were (for cost) not from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not works of art, it was their role as models, it was merely works of exhibition.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted the permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at the time have rightly entered the art and auction history as an authorised original Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Boxes with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached more than 100 000 dollars at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that it had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968 and that Warhol had left him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined three of Swedish private owners, two of whom were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press records were first grounded and flattened, and white oil paint was then applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the colour with a painting roll was applied directly to the press plate without a foundation, and that it is not oil but acrylic colour.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced that it would follow the "heavy accusations" raised in the matter of soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, one has been shrouded in inexorable silence.
